{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493354"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1297"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1297"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.15,0.03,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46377"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the pre-admission clinic seven days before his scheduled elective total hip arthroplasty. He has a history of bilateral hip osteoarthritis with chronic pain, hypertension, chronic kidney disease stage 4, and non-valvular atrial fibrillation. His medications include warfarin 5 mg daily and amlodipine. He has been on warfarin for two years with stable INR values; his most recent INR was 2.5. His BMI is 28 kg/m\u00b2. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The plan is to cease warfarin five days before surgery and check his INR the day before the procedure. He underwent uncomplicated total hip arthroplasty and was seen on ward round day one post-operatively, with haemostasis achieved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach to managing his post-operative venous thromboembolism risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enoxaparin 20 mg daily and restart warfarin 5 mg daily","Unfractionated heparin 5000 units twice daily","Dabigatran 150 mg twice daily","Pneumatic compression device and compression stockings","Warfarin 5 mg daily alone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires careful management of anticoagulation perioperatively due to his non-valvular atrial fibrillation and the thrombotic risk associated with major orthopaedic surgery. With hypertension, age over 65, and chronic kidney disease, his CHA\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003EDS\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E-VASc score is 4-5, placing him at intermediate risk for thromboembolism. Hence, post-operative bridging anticoagulation is not required. However, all patients undergoing hip arthroplasty are at high risk for venous thromboembolism (VTE) and require appropriate prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin 20 mg daily and restart warfarin 5 mg daily\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Due to the patient\u0027s chronic kidney disease stage 4, the standard prophylactic dose of enoxaparin (40 mg) must be reduced to 20 mg daily to account for decreased renal clearance. This provides immediate post-operative VTE prophylaxis while warfarin is restarted at the patient\u0027s usual maintenance dose. This approach avoids the prothrombotic state associated with warfarin loading doses and minimises bleeding risk. The enoxaparin can be discontinued once the INR reaches therapeutic range (2.0-3.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfractionated heparin 5000 units twice daily\u003C/strong\u003E is another option for VTE prophylaxis; however, this option does not address the need to restart long-term anticoagulation with warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDabigatran 150 mg twice daily\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this setting. While dabigatran can be used for non-valvular atrial fibrillation and VTE prophylaxis post total hip arthroplasty, it is contraindicated in patients with chronic kidney disease stage 4 due to significantly reduced renal clearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumatic compression device and compression stockings\u003C/strong\u003E provide useful mechanical prophylaxis but are insufficient as sole therapy in this patient. These should be used as adjuncts to pharmacological prophylaxis rather than replacements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin 5 mg daily alone\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate because warfarin takes several days to achieve therapeutic anticoagulation. The patient would remain unprotected during the immediate post-operative period when thrombotic risk is highest.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warfarin should be recommenced post-operatively as soon as haemostasis has been achieved.","In addition to the thromboembolic risk, the patient\u0027s risk of VTE post-surgery also needs to be considered."],"references":["Witt DM, Clark NP, Kaatz S, Schnurr T, Ansell JE. Guidance for the practical management of warfarin therapy in the treatment of venous thromboembolism. Journal of Thrombosis and Thrombolysis. 2016 Jan;41(1):187-205.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Periprocedural management of patients with cardiovascular disease. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines; 2023 Jun."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94848"}},"question"